{{for|the Honduran football club|Palestino FC}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} {{More citations needed|date=May 2010}} {{Infobox football club | clubname = Palestino | image = Club Deportivo Palestino badge.svg | image_size = 180px | fullname = Club Deportivo Palestino S.A.D.P. | nickname = ''Tino'', ''Árabes'', ''Tricolor'', ''Baisanos'' | ground = [[Estadio Municipal de La Cisterna]] | capacity = 8,000 | founded = 20 August 1920 | chairman = Jorge Uauy | coach = [[Ivo Basay]] | league = [[Primera División de Chile|Campeonato Nacional]] | season = [[2017 Chilean Primera División|2017 Transición]] | position = 15th | current = | website = http://www.palestino.cl/ | pattern_la1 = _palestino15h | pattern_la2=_palestino2014a | pattern_b2 = _palestino2014a | pattern_ra1 = _palestino15h | pattern_ra2 = _palestino2014a1 | pattern_sh1 = _palestino15h | pattern_sh2=_palestino2014a |pattern_so1=_palestino15h |pattern_so2=_palestino2013a | leftarm1=FFFFFF | leftarm2=000000 | body1 = FFFFFF | body2 = 000000 | rightarm1 = FFFFFF | rightarm2 = 000000 | shorts1 = FFFFFF | shorts2 = 000000 | socks1 = 000000 | socks2 = 000000 | pattern_b1 = _palestino15h }}
'''Club Deportivo Palestino''' is a professional [[association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Santiago, Chile]]. The club was founded in 1920 and plays in the [[Primera División de Chile]]. They play their home games at the [[Estadio Municipal de La Cisterna]] stadium, which has a capacity of approximately 8,000 seats.
==History== The club was founded on 20 August 1920, when they participated in a colonial competition in [[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]]. It was founded by a group of [[Palestinian diaspora|Palestinian immigrants]]; the name of the club reflects the origin in [[Palestinian community in Chile|Chile's Palestinian community]]. In 1952 the [[Federación de Fútbol de Chile]] set up the first professional leagues. Palestino was accepted into the [[Chilean Primera División B|Second Division]], which they won to ascertain promotion to the [[Primera División de Chile|Primera División]].
In 1955 the club won their first national championship under the coaching of Argentine captain ''Guillermo Coll'', in that era the club became known by the nickname ''millonario'' (Millionaire) because of their ability to attract top class footballers.
In 1978 the club won their second league title, this time the team was led by Chilean captain [[Elías Figueroa]]. In this campaign they set a new record in the domestic tournament, for the number of games unbeaten and soon won the [[Copa Chile]] to claim the league and cup double.
In 2004 the club became a registered company, but the change of status did not bring the expected improvement in results. In 2006 they finished in 18th place out of 20 teams, forcing them to face a play-off against [[Club Deportivo Arturo Fernández Vial|Fernandez Vial]] to keep their place in the top flight. Ultimately the club would triumph thus preserving their spot within the Chilean first division.
The club made a surprising run to the final of the [[Primera División Chilena 2008|Clausura 2008 tournament]], where they lost to champions [[Colo-Colo]]. Following this success, the club intends to float on the Chilean and Palestinian stock exchanges.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Reuters]]|author=Cerda, Claudio|title=Chile's Palestino tapping roots to go public|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/sow/news?slug=reu-latamchile_pix_tv&prov=reuters&type=lgns|date=17 August 2009|accessdate=2009-08-17}}</ref>
In January 2014, Palestino was fined the equivalent of $1,300 for using a new team jersey with the club's traditional colors, red, green and black, and with the number one shaped as the map of [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] before the creation of Israel. Chilean Jewish groups complained, with a formal complaint to their national Federation being made by Patrick Kiblisky, owner of first-division club [[Ñublense]]. The jerseys were said to have been first used in December 2013, although the club said they were used in the prior season. The federation banned the shirts and fined the club by the grounds that the Federation is opposed to "any form of political, religious, sexual, ethnic, social or racial discrimination". On its Facebook page, the club stated: "For us, free Palestine will always be historical Palestine, nothing less."<ref>{{cite web|title=Chile bans Palestino football club 'anti-Israel' shirt|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25821058|publisher=BBC}}</ref>
